The mentioned reduction in revenues and increase in costs means that the already low EIRR for the construction of the border section of the d 8 is not achieved.
The construction of the nearby section of the d 8 is therefore economically inefficient.
Cost increases also occurred in the construction of the a 17 as in the construction of the two above-mentioned sections of the d 8.
In the context of the macroeconomic assessment of the Federal Transport Roadmap in 1992, the Federal Ministry of Transport expected investment costs of approximately €320 million.
It thus identified a benefit / cost ratio of 4.6.
Meanwhile, costs have increased to around €670 million and the benefit / cost ratio has decreased by more than half.
Independently of the parallel audits carried out with the Sao between 2003 and 2005, the BRH had assessed the cost-effectiveness of the planning and construction of the A17 motorway.
It noted that the approval authority required a non-necessary landscape tunnel for the third section of the a 17.
The BRH succeeded in convincing the Federal Ministry and the road administration of the superfluous landscape tunnel during the audit.
This avoided €10 million in construction costs and €150 000 in annual operating costs.
When examining the first section of a 17, the BRH found that the construction measure was inadequately prepared.
The following example illustrates this:
During the planning phase, the road administration refrained from measuring the state of the rock on the surface of the Dölzschener Wand as it was difficult to access.
Only when the tunnel drive reached the wall did it catch up.
It appeared that the rock was more weathered than it was supposed to be during the tendering procedure.
Costly measures such as anchorages, injections and impact protection networks for around €3.3 million were needed.
The road administration not only carried the costs of additional services, which were already necessary, such as the safeguarding of the Dölzschener Wand, but also those which would not have been necessary for proper construction preparation.
This includes expenditure due to disturbed construction operations (€3.2 million), additional recruitment of the front team (€0.5 million) and increased wages and material prices due to the extension of construction time (€7 million).
This increase in spending of around €10.7 million does not represent any continuing added value.
The BRH took these and other measures to encourage the Federal Ministry to better exercise its supervision of major road construction activities.
In this context, it should be urgent for road construction administrations to introduce quality assurance systems.
Benefits of cooperation for BRH and Sao The cooperation met the expectations of both Courts of Auditors.
The BRH received insights into the planning, procurement and implementation of the construction of the border bridge.
Both invoicing offices have developed a stock of data on bridge and tunnel prices that will help in future audits.
The Sao found that the main construction parameters for bridges, tunnels and tracks of the d 8 are not different from those of the a 17.
The auditors of both Courts involved in the cooperation have gained valuable experience which will be useful for future audits.
